table-1408-284.caption: Cases
data: "Incidentally, one of the more surprising things I discovered while researching the articles for this book is that a number of them exactly mirrored a Wikipedia entry on the same subject. I didn't find any exact copies of Wikipedia in the articles in this book, but the structure often was the same and used the same citations in the same places. If I had to guess, I'd say that half of all the "original" articles covered in this book are Wikipedia entry rewrites. If not more. It certainly makes me wonder about the rest of the articles I didn't research. Wikipedia accuracy concerns aside, that's just not cool. Or perhaps that's how the Wikipedia articles were generated in the first place. Due to the obscurity of certain details in some of the articles, and the fact that none of those details showed up in a Google search on the same subject, I am more inclined to believe reporters borrow heavily from Wikipedia, and not the other way around."

Withdrawn by NZR in 1985 sold to Ravensdown Fertiliser who used as their shunter at Hornby until 2002. In poor mechanical condition, D SA 261 was dismantled for overhaul but this did not proceed and the locomotive remains were stored in the Christchurch depot sidings. This locomotive was sold to a private owner in Dunedin in 2009 and is being restored to running order. TMS DSA 658.

table-1408-172.caption: List of NZ locomotives
data: Owned by Les Hostick. Previously on static display at Te Awamutu Railway Museum, leased to Mainline Steam in 1994. Restored to mainline standard in 1999, although certification has since lapsed. Currently at the Parnell depot, B A 552 is having work associated with a major boiler survey and minor mechanical repairs done.

Owned by Les Hostick. Previously on static display at Te Awamutu Railway Museum, leased to Mainline Steam in 1994. Restoration work at Parnell began in 2001 after the restoration of J B 1236 was finished and is currently ongoing. It is not intended that B B 144 will be certified for mainline operation.

The boiler of J A 1256 was purchased privately after the locomotive was withdrawn from service by NZR. It was donated to Mainline Steam in May 2012 and is stored at the Christchurch depot as a spare boiler for any of the Trust's preserved 4-8-2s.

Purchased by Les Hostick & syndicate 1971, and placed on static display at the Te Awamutu Railway Museum in 1972. Sold to Ian Welch in 2008 following an ownership dispute, and moved to Parnell for eventual restoration. J A 1267 is currently in storage and will be restored as a coal burner.
The tender of J A 1270 was purchased as a spare in the early 1970s after the locomotive was withdrawn from service. It is currently stored at Parnell as a spare for any of the Trust's 4-8-2s.

Purchased by Les Hostick 1967. Placed on static display at the Te Awamutu Railway Museum in 1968, before being leased to Mainline Steam in 1994. Moved to Parnell 1994 for restoration to mainline use. Overhauled 2000-4. Boiler certificate expires in 2014.
The tender of K A 939 was purchased by Ian Welch as a spare tender for K 911 and K A 942. It is currently stored at Parnell.

Preserved by Ferrymead Trust through the efforts of Cyril Evans. Ran at Ferrymead in limited service until 1995, before leased to Mainline Steam and moved to Christchurch depot. Restoration began in 2006 with the intention of mainline operation. K B 968 is currently based at the Christchurch depot.
Purchased as motorless and alternatorless hulk by Ian Welch. Moved to Upper Hutt depot, later to Plimmerton depot. DJ 3292 is currently under restoration to mainline use. Formerly D J 1228.
Purchased from the New Zealand Dairy Company, who used it at their Waharoa plant until replaced by DSC 2067. Used as the yard shunter at Parnell Depot.
Occasional yard shunter at Plimmerton Depot (Wellington), in service. Formerly D SC 469, the last member of the class built.
Used as the yard shunter at Plimmerton Depot. Originally T R 151.

Built for Milburn Cement, Burnside. Sold to Mainline Steam 1988, moved to Christchurch depot and used as yard shunter. Overhauled in 2006, painted in “Fruit Salad” colours. Price 213 is currently undergoing engine replacement at Christchurch Depot.

Owned by Mainline Steam. Purchased from original owner Tasman Forestry by the late Mark Coldstream, passing into MLST ownership after his death in 2006. Stored unserviceable at Parnell depot (Auckland).

Killed in an ambush by a special unit of the French police, while trying to release from prison his friend Bruno Sulak. Stiv and Bruno were the forerunner of today's pink panther group.
A Yugoslav amateur boxer, streetfighter and gangster, during the 70's and 80's he operated his own gang in Germany and was killed in 1986 by rival Goran Vuković "Majmun".

One of the closest friends of Giška. He was the owner of 70 auto waste in the largest auto waste in the Netherlands. One of the founders and major financers Serbian Guard. He was killed outside his family home on the doorstep on August 4, 1991.
Killed in Gospić on 15 September 1991 during battle. There are strong indications that he was killed by his own men.
One of the infamous mob bosses of the older generation. He was murdered on October 1, 1993 by a sole hitman.

Georg Stanković's son, he was murdered on June 23, 1996 by a sole hitman.

A Belgrade gangster involved with drugs and killings. His uncle was Pavle Bulatović, the late Defense Minister. Murdered on June 30, 1998, in his cafe "Koloseum" in Dedinje by a sole hitman.
He was clan member of Ljubomir Magas during 1980's, and the owner of FC Zeleznik. One of Arkan's closest friends, killed in 1998.

Considered the most powerful criminal in Serbia until his assassination in 15 January 2000 .
Murdered while returning from the funeral of Branislav Lainović on March 23, 2000 by the Zemun clan.

Milivoje Matović "Miša Kobra", arrived to Sydney in 1986 and became a known gambler who organized big games. His younger brother Braca owed money to the gang of Žorž Stanković, Žorž sent his son Batica for Miša Kobra whose friend Boža Cvetić threw down the street after he had pointed a gun at them. Batica was deported to Serbia and Braca was killed in the meantime. Žorž was killed in 1993 and his son Batica in 1996.

Head of one of the largest Serbian criminal groups on record, the Zemun clan.The peak of this cartel's influence occurred from 2000 until 2003 when Spasojević was killed by Serbian police on March 27, 2003 during a country-wide manhunt initiated after the assassination of Serbian Prime Minister Zoran Đinđić.

data: "Easter": Sal discovers an old planning application to convert the barn in the field behind her house and, despite the fact that it is officially too late to object, she enlists the help of the Guild in an effort to stop the development. "Working From Home":
"Dinner Party": Caroline is planning a dinner party for husband John and his friends from London. "Missing Persons": The ladies of Clatterford stage a fashion show.

"New Beginnings": Spike and Tash are finally ready to travel the world in their converted mobile library, but a confusion with the gears leads to a call-out for the emergency services, and Sal's house ends up looking like a war zone. Jock agrees to mend the damage, and the thawing of his previously frosty relationship with Sal continues, much to the amusement of Tip and the disgust of Tash. "Ladies in Lavender": All bets are off, though, when it is finally revealed that the barn is not being converted for Charles Dance at all - Jock just let Rosie jump to that conclusion to get the Guild off his back. This would be bad enough if Jock hadn't promised the Guild an appearance by Mr Dance as their next (and indeed, first) celebrity speaker.
